Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The Khoi and San communities have always been considered original knowledge holders of rooibos. Now the community will finally be able to enjoy its share of the industry. READ: Rooibos tea: EU protection is good news for South Africa Following the 2019 agreement, more than R12-million will be disbursed into trusts for the benefit of the Khoi and San communities. The National Khoi and San council says this has been a long and daunting journey. WATCH: Investigating the anti-inflammatory effects of rooibos Cecil le Fleur, National Khoi and San council chairperson, said: "It was really a winding road, a very difficult road to travel. "We started long ago with the negotiations not only on the recognition of our rights to rooibos tea or knowledge of that tea but also to be recognised South Africa's indigenous people. "We found the Rooibos Council in a total state of denial. They refused to recognise that the Khoi and San people were the first primary knowledge holders of the plant."